# bun.lock Proxy Stripping

Local installs may route through a private npm proxy/registry, which bakes the
proxy URL into the resolution (second) field of each package entry in
`bun.lock`. That host-specific URL must never land in a PR.

## Before Creating Any PR

1. **Always** clear the proxy/resolution field in `bun.lock` first.
2. Do **not** match on a specific host name — clear the field for **any** npm
   registry tarball URL, leaving it as `""` (the value Bun uses for the default
   registry).
3. Stage the cleaned `bun.lock` before opening the PR.

## What to Strip

Each package entry is an array of the form:

```
"<key>": ["<name>@<version>", "<resolution>", { ...deps }, "<integrity>"]
```

The **second element** is the resolution/proxy field. When it points at a
registry tarball it must be reset to an empty string.

- With proxy:

```
"readdirp/picomatch": ["picomatch@2.3.2", "https://proxy.npm.your-company.com/picomatch/-/picomatch-2.3.2.tgz", {}, "sha512-V7+vQEJ06Z+c5tSye8S+nHUfI51xoXIXjHQ99cQtKUkQqqO1kO/KCJUfZXuB47h/YBlDhah2H3hdUGXn8ie0oA=="]
```

- After stripping:

```
"readdirp/picomatch": ["picomatch@2.3.2", "", {}, "sha512-V7+vQEJ06Z+c5tSye8S+nHUfI51xoXIXjHQ99cQtKUkQqqO1kO/KCJUfZXuB47h/YBlDhah2H3hdUGXn8ie0oA=="]
```

## How to Strip

Use the project's TypeScript script (run by Bun). It is host-agnostic: it
matches any `http(s)` registry tarball URL (`.../-/<name>-<version>.tgz`)
sitting in the resolution slot and replaces only that URL with `""`. Git,
GitHub, file, and already-empty resolutions are left untouched.

```bash
bun run strip-lock-proxy
```

The logic lives in [`scripts/strip-bun-lock-proxy.ts`](../../scripts/strip-bun-lock-proxy.ts).

Verify nothing remains before committing (exits non-zero if any proxy URL is
still present, so it doubles as a CI / pre-PR gate):

```bash
bun run strip-lock-proxy:check
```

## Automated via Git Hook

A committed pre-commit hook does this automatically whenever `bun.lock` is
staged. It lives at [`.githooks/pre-commit`](../../.githooks/pre-commit) and
delegates to any globally-configured hooks first (e.g. anything set globally on your machine) so those are preserved.

Activate it once per clone (also runs automatically on `bun install` via the
`prepare` script):

```bash
bun run setup-hooks   # git config core.hooksPath .githooks
```

The hook is a safety net, not a replacement for the rule — still run the strip
and `:check` before opening a PR.

## Rules

- **Never open a PR with proxy URLs in `bun.lock`.**
- Keep the strip logic host-agnostic — do not hardcode a proxy hostname.
- Only the resolution field is cleared; names, versions, dependency maps, and
  integrity hashes are never modified.
